I utilized the OpenCV library to perform "Image Preprocessing" techniques. 
By applying different mathematical kernels (filters), I transformed a raw image into several variations: Grayscale (removing color to focus on intensity), Gaussian Blur (smoothing noise), and Canny Edge Detection (finding boundaries). 
This lab demonstrated how computer vision models "simplify" an image before trying to identify objects within it.

import cv2

img = cv2.imread('image.jpg')
gray = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
blur = cv2.GaussianBlur(gray, (5, 5), 0)
edges = cv2.Canny(blur, 100, 200)

cv2.imshow('Edges', edges)
cv2.waitKey(0)

Feature Simplification: Learned that grayscaling reduces data volume by 66% (from 3 channels to 1) without losing structural information.
Noise Reduction: Understood how "blurring" helps a model ignore small, irrelevant details (like graininess) and focus on large shapes.
Gradient Mathematics: Mastered the concept of "Edges"—the points where pixel intensity changes sharply (calculated using derivatives).
Preprocessing Pipeline: Developed a logical workflow for preparing visual data for Machine Learning models.
